{
  "The 'master gland' that controls many other endocrine glands is the:": "",
  "Pineal": "",
  "Thyroid": "",
  "Adrenal": "",
  "Pituitary": "",
  "The pituitary gland is called the master gland because its hormones (TSH, ACTH, FSH, LH, GH, prolactin) regulate the activity of many other endocrine glands throughout the body.": "",
  "Growth hormone (GH) is produced by the:": "",
  "Posterior pituitary": "",
  "Anterior pituitary": "",
  "Adrenal cortex": "",
  "Thyroid gland": "",
  "Growth hormone is synthesized and secreted by somatotroph cells in the anterior pituitary gland, stimulating growth, cell reproduction, and regeneration throughout the body.": "",
  "ADH and oxytocin are stored and released by the:": "",
  "Adrenal medulla": "",
  "Although ADH and oxytocin are synthesized in the hypothalamus, they are transported along axons to the posterior pituitary, where they are stored and released into the bloodstream when needed.": "",
  "T3 and T4 from the thyroid gland primarily regulate:": "",
  "Blood pressure only": "",
  "Blood clotting factors": "",
  "Metabolism, energy production, and heat generation": "",
  "Reproduction exclusively": "",
  "Thyroid hormones T3 and T4 are the primary regulators of basal metabolic rate, increasing oxygen consumption, heat production, and energy expenditure in virtually every tissue of the body.": "",
  "Calcitonin is produced by the _____ and _____ blood calcium.": "",
  "Thyroid gland; lowers": "",
  "Parathyroid glands; raises": "",
  "Pituitary gland; raises": "",
  "Adrenal glands; has no effect on": "",
  "Calcitonin is secreted by parafollicular (C) cells of the thyroid gland in response to high blood calcium, and it lowers calcium levels by inhibiting osteoclast activity and promoting calcium deposition into bone.": "",
  "Cortisol is produced by the:": "",
  "Cortisol is a glucocorticoid steroid hormone produced specifically by the zona fasciculata of the adrenal cortex, playing critical roles in stress response, metabolism, and immune regulation.": "",
  "Epinephrine is produced by the:": "",
  "Pancreas": "",
  "Epinephrine (adrenaline) is produced by chromaffin cells in the adrenal medulla, which functions as a modified sympathetic ganglion releasing catecholamines during the fight-or-flight response.": "",
  "Insulin is produced by _____ cells in the pancreatic islets.": "",
  "Beta": "",
  "Gamma": "",
  "Delta": "",
  "Alpha": "",
  "Beta cells in the islets of Langerhans produce insulin, the hormone responsible for lowering blood glucose by facilitating glucose uptake into cells and promoting glycogen storage.": "",
  "Melatonin is produced by the _____ gland and regulates:": "",
  "Pineal; sleep-wake cycles": "",
  "Adrenal; blood pressure": "",
  "Pituitary; metabolism": "",
  "Thyroid; calcium levels": "",
  "The pineal gland produces melatonin in response to darkness, helping to regulate circadian rhythms and the sleep-wake cycle by signaling the brain that it is nighttime.": "",
  "Aldosterone is produced by the adrenal cortex and regulates:": "",
  "Sodium and potassium balance and blood pressure": "",
  "Blood sugar levels": "",
  "Calcium balance": "",
  "Thyroid function": "",
  "Aldosterone is a mineralocorticoid produced by the zona glomerulosa of the adrenal cortex that promotes sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion in the kidneys, thereby regulating blood volume and pressure.": "",
  "What is the anterior pituitary?": "",
  "The glandular portion of the pituitary that synthesizes and secretes its own tropic hormones including GH, TSH, ACTH, FSH, LH, and prolactin": "",
  "The part of the pituitary that stores hormones made by the hypothalamus": "",
  "A separate gland located above the hypothalamus": "",
  "The portion of the adrenal gland that produces cortisol": "",
  "The anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis) is the glandular lobe of the pituitary gland that independently synthesizes and secretes multiple hormones including growth hormone, TSH, ACTH, FSH, LH, and prolactin in response to hypothalamic releasing hormones.": "",
  "What is the posterior pituitary?": "",
  "A bone structure at the base of the skull": "",
  "A neural extension of the hypothalamus that stores and releases ADH and oxytocin, which are produced by hypothalamic neurons": "",
  "The gland that produces melatonin": "",
  "The part of the pituitary that synthesizes its own hormones independently": "",
  "The posterior pituitary (neurohypophysis) is not a true gland but a neural extension of the hypothalamus that stores and releases ADH and oxytocin, which are manufactured in the hypothalamic nuclei and transported along axons to the posterior lobe.": "",
  "What is TSH?": "",
  "A steroid hormone produced by the adrenal cortex": "",
  "A type of thyroid cancer marker": "",
  "A hormone produced by the thyroid that regulates metabolism": "",
  "Thyroid-stimulating hormone, produced by the anterior pituitary to stimulate the thyroid gland to produce T3 and T4": "",
  "TSH (thyroid-stimulating hormone or thyrotropin) is a tropic hormone secreted by the anterior pituitary that acts on the thyroid gland to stimulate the production and release of T3 and T4 thyroid hormones.": "",
  "What is ACTH?": "",
  "Adrenocorticotropic hormone, produced by the anterior pituitary to stimulate the adrenal cortex to produce cortisol": "",
  "A neurotransmitter in the autonomic nervous system": "",
  "A calcium-regulating hormone from the parathyroids": "",
  "A hormone produced by the adrenal cortex that raises blood sugar": "",
  "ACTH (adrenocorticotropic hormone) is a tropic hormone from the anterior pituitary that stimulates the adrenal cortex, specifically the zona fasciculata, to synthesize and secrete cortisol as part of the HPA axis.": "",
  "What is PTH (parathyroid hormone)?": "",
  "A pancreatic hormone that regulates blood sugar by promoting glucose uptake into cells and stimulating glycogen synthesis in the liver and skeletal muscles": "",
  "A hormone produced by the parafollicular C cells of the thyroid gland that lowers blood calcium by inhibiting osteoclast activity and promoting calcium deposition in bone": "",
  "A pituitary hormone that controls longitudinal bone growth and overall somatic development by stimulating hepatic production of insulin-like growth factors": "",
  "A hormone secreted by the parathyroid glands that raises blood calcium by stimulating bone resorption, renal calcium reabsorption, and vitamin D activation": "",
  "Parathyroid hormone (PTH) is secreted by the four parathyroid glands in response to low blood calcium and works through three mechanisms: stimulating osteoclasts to release calcium from bone, increasing renal calcium reabsorption, and activating vitamin D to enhance intestinal calcium absorption.": "",
  "What does prolactin do?": "",
  "It stimulates milk production in mammary glands after childbirth": "",
  "It raises blood calcium levels by acting on bone": "",
  "It stimulates growth of long bones during puberty": "",
  "It controls the sleep-wake cycle": "",
  "Prolactin is an anterior pituitary hormone whose primary function is to stimulate milk production (lactation) in the mammary glands, with its levels rising significantly during pregnancy and after childbirth.": "",
  "What is the thymus gland?": "",
  "A part of the adrenal gland that secretes catecholamines, located deep within the adrenal medulla superior to the kidneys": "",
  "An endocrine gland that produces thyroid hormones T3 and T4 in the anterior neck, regulated by TSH from the anterior pituitary": "",
  "An endocrine and lymphoid organ located behind the sternum that produces thymosin, essential for T-cell maturation and immune function": "",
  "A gland located on the posterior surface of the thyroid in the neck that regulates calcium homeostasis through parathyroid hormone": "",
  "The thymus is a bilobed organ behind the sternum that functions as both an endocrine gland (producing thymosin) and a lymphoid organ critical for the development and maturation of T lymphocytes, especially during childhood.": "",
  "What are the islets of Langerhans?": "",
  "Small islands of tissue in the thyroid gland that produce calcitonin": "",
  "Groups of neurons in the hypothalamus": "",
  "Lymph nodes located in the abdomen": "",
  "Clusters of endocrine cells within the pancreas that produce insulin (beta cells), glucagon (alpha cells), and somatostatin (delta cells)": "",
  "The islets of Langerhans are scattered clusters of endocrine cells embedded within the exocrine tissue of the pancreas, containing alpha cells (glucagon), beta cells (insulin), and delta cells (somatostatin) that collectively regulate blood glucose homeostasis.": "",
  "What does FSH mean?": "",
  "Fluid-secreting hormone, produced by the kidneys": "",
  "Fat-storage hormone, produced by adipose tissue": "",
  "Fast-signaling hormone, a type of neurotransmitter": "",
  "Follicle-stimulating hormone, an anterior pituitary gonadotropin that stimulates follicle development in females and spermatogenesis in males": "",
  "Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) is a gonadotropin secreted by the anterior pituitary that promotes ovarian follicle growth and estrogen production in females and supports spermatogenesis in the testes of males.": "",
  "What is glucagon?": "",
  "A digestive enzyme that breaks down glycogen in the intestine": "",
  "A hormone that lowers blood glucose by promoting cellular uptake": "",
  "A hormone produced by alpha cells of the pancreatic islets that raises blood glucose by stimulating glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis in the liver": "",
  "Glucagon is a peptide hormone secreted by pancreatic alpha cells in response to low blood glucose, acting primarily on the liver to stimulate glycogenolysis (glycogen breakdown) and gluconeogenesis (new glucose synthesis) to raise blood sugar levels.": "",
  "A 10-year-old child is significantly shorter than peers of the same age. After a thorough evaluation, the pediatric endocrinologist finds that the child has very low levels of growth hormone. Which gland is most likely not functioning properly?": "",
  "Growth hormone is produced by somatotroph cells of the anterior pituitary, so a deficiency in GH production indicates anterior pituitary dysfunction, which can lead to pituitary dwarfism if untreated during childhood.": "",
  "A patient in the emergency department is severely dehydrated. The physician explains that the patient's body should be releasing a hormone to conserve water. Which hormone and gland are involved in this water-conservation response?": "",
  "Aldosterone from the adrenal medulla": "",
  "Insulin from the pancreatic beta cells": "",
  "Calcitonin from the thyroid gland": "",
  "ADH (antidiuretic hormone) released from the posterior pituitary": "",
  "Dehydration increases blood osmolarity, which is detected by osmoreceptors in the hypothalamus, triggering the release of ADH from the posterior pituitary to promote water reabsorption in the kidneys and produce more concentrated urine.": "",
  "A nursing student is caring for a postpartum mother who is breastfeeding. The student learns that a specific pituitary hormone stimulates milk production. Which hormone is this, and where is it produced?": "",
  "TSH from the anterior pituitary": "",
  "Oxytocin from the posterior pituitary": "",
  "Estrogen from the ovaries": "",
  "Prolactin from the anterior pituitary": "",
  "Prolactin, produced by lactotroph cells of the anterior pituitary, is the primary hormone responsible for stimulating milk synthesis in the mammary glands, while oxytocin from the posterior pituitary triggers the let-down reflex for milk ejection.": "",
  "A patient presents with muscle cramps, tingling in the fingers, and a blood test reveals dangerously low calcium levels. The physician suspects a problem with a small gland embedded in the thyroid. Which gland and hormone are most likely involved?": "",
  "The adrenal gland and cortisol": "",
  "The thyroid gland and calcitonin": "",
  "The parathyroid glands and parathyroid hormone (PTH)": "",
  "The pituitary gland and growth hormone": "",
  "Low blood calcium (hypocalcemia) with symptoms like muscle cramps and tetany suggests parathyroid gland dysfunction, since PTH is the primary hormone responsible for raising blood calcium through bone resorption, renal reabsorption, and vitamin D activation.": "",
  "During a stressful exam, a student feels her heart racing, palms sweating, and breathing becoming rapid. Her professor explains that a specific gland released hormones causing this fight-or-flight response. Which gland is primarily responsible?": "",
  "The thyroid gland": "",
  "The anterior pituitary": "",
  "The pineal gland": "",
  "The adrenal medulla": "",
  "The adrenal medulla releases catecholamines (primarily epinephrine and norepinephrine) during sympathetic nervous system activation, producing the classic fight-or-flight responses including increased heart rate, sweating, and bronchodilation.": "",
  "A 45-year-old woman complains of unexplained weight gain, constant fatigue, and feeling cold all the time. Her physician suspects a problem with a butterfly-shaped gland in her neck. Which gland and its hormones are most likely involved?": "",
  "The thyroid gland and its hormones T3/T4": "",
  "The parathyroid glands and PTH": "",
  "The adrenal glands and cortisol": "",
  "The pancreas and insulin": "",
  "Symptoms of weight gain, fatigue, and cold intolerance are classic signs of hypothyroidism, where the thyroid gland produces insufficient T3 and T4 hormones that normally regulate metabolic rate, energy production, and heat generation.": "",
  "A patient has a blood glucose level of 350 mg/dL after eating. A medical student asks the attending physician which cells in the pancreas should respond to bring glucose down. What is the correct answer?": "",
  "Delta cells, which release somatostatin to lower glucose": "",
  "Beta cells, which release insulin to promote glucose uptake by cells": "",
  "Alpha cells, which release glucagon to store excess glucose": "",
  "Acinar cells, which release digestive enzymes to break down glucose": "",
  "Beta cells in the islets of Langerhans detect elevated blood glucose and respond by secreting insulin, which promotes glucose uptake into muscle and fat cells, stimulates glycogen synthesis in the liver, and thereby lowers blood sugar levels.": "",
  "A shift worker who rotates between day and night shifts reports chronic insomnia and difficulty maintaining a normal sleep schedule. An endocrinologist explains that a small brain gland is being disrupted by irregular light exposure. Which gland and hormone are involved?": "",
  "The pineal gland and melatonin": "",
  "The pituitary and prolactin": "",
  "The adrenal medulla and epinephrine": "",
  "The hypothalamus and CRH": "",
  "The pineal gland secretes melatonin in response to darkness, and irregular light-dark cycles from shift work disrupt normal melatonin secretion patterns, leading to circadian rhythm disorders and insomnia.": "",
  "A medical student notices that a patient on long-term steroid therapy has developed high blood pressure and sodium retention. The attending explains that the prescribed steroids are mimicking the effects of a natural adrenal hormone. Which hormone is being mimicked?": "",
  "Epinephrine": "",
  "Melatonin": "",
  "Insulin": "",
  "Aldosterone": "",
  "The symptoms of sodium retention and hypertension suggest mineralocorticoid effects similar to aldosterone, which promotes sodium reabsorption in the kidneys; some synthetic steroids have cross-reactivity with mineralocorticoid receptors, producing these side effects.": "",
  "A child is brought to the pediatrician because of frequent infections. Blood work reveals very low T-cell counts. The physician suspects a problem with an endocrine organ that is critical for immune cell development during childhood. Which gland is most likely dysfunctional?": "",
  "The thymus gland": "",
  "The adrenal glands": "",
  "The thymus is essential for T-cell maturation during childhood, producing thymosin and providing the microenvironment where T lymphocytes develop and learn to distinguish self from non-self; thymic dysfunction leads to immunodeficiency and increased susceptibility to infections.": ""
}